<!-- HERO -->
   <section class="bg-[linear-gradient(rgba(30,41,59,.85),rgba(30,41,59,.75)),url(&#39;https://legalx24.com/img/divorce.jpg&#39;)] bg-cover bg-center text-white text-center px-5 py-[140px]"> 
      <h1 class="text-[clamp(38px,4vw,54px)] font-extrabold mb-4"> Divorce Proceedings &amp; Legal Representation </h1> 
      <p class="max-w-[850px] mx-auto text-[18px] leading-[1.9] opacity-95"> Divorce is the formal legal dissolution of a valid marriage through judicial intervention. It terminates marital obligations, restructures legal relationships between spouses, and resolves claims arising out of the matrimonial bond in accordance with applicable personal laws. Divorce proceedings require careful legal drafting, evidentiary support, and structured representation before the competent Family Court. </p> </section> 
   <section class="px-5 py-[70px]"> 
      <div class="max-w-[1100px] mx-auto">
         <h2 class="text-[clamp(26px,3vw,34px)] font-extrabold mb-5 text-slate-800 relative after:content-[&#39;&#39;] after:block after:w-[70px] after:h-1 after:bg-pink-600 after:mt-2 after:rounded"> What is Divorce? </h2>
         <p class="text-[16px] leading-[2] text-slate-600 mb-3"> Divorce is a judicial remedy through which a marriage is legally dissolved by a decree of a competent court. Once the decree is granted, the matrimonial relationship ceases to exist in the eyes of law, and the parties are restored to their independent legal status. </p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2] mb-3"> Divorce proceedings are governed by personal laws applicable to the parties, and the court examines whether statutory grounds have been established. The burden of proof, procedural compliance, and presentation of evidence play a decisive role in the outcome of the case. </p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2]"> Proper legal guidance ensures that rights are safeguarded, procedural requirements are fulfilled, and disputes are resolved in a structured and dignified manner. </p>
      </div> </section> 
   <section class="bg-purple-50 border-y border-purple-100 px-5 py-[70px]"> 
      <div class="max-w-[1100px] mx-auto bg-white p-10 rounded-[18px] shadow-xl">
         <h2 class="text-[clamp(26px,3vw,34px)] font-extrabold mb-5 text-slate-800 relative after:content-[&#39;&#39;] after:block after:w-[70px] after:h-1 after:bg-pink-600 after:mt-2 after:rounded"> Types of Divorce </h2>
         <p class="font-semibold">1. Mutual Consent Divorce</p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2] mb-3"> Mutual consent divorce is initiated when both spouses voluntarily agree that the marriage has irretrievably broken down and cannot be sustained. A joint petition is filed before the Family Court, affirming that the parties have been living separately and mutually consent to dissolve the marriage. </p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2] mb-4"> The court verifies the voluntary nature of consent, examines settlement terms, and upon satisfaction, grants a decree dissolving the marriage. Consent must be free, informed, and continuing until final decree. </p>
         <p class="font-semibold">2. Contested Divorce</p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2] mb-3"> A contested divorce is filed by one spouse against the other on legally recognized statutory grounds. In such cases, the petitioner must establish the alleged ground through documentary evidence and witness testimony. </p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2]"> The court conducts hearings, records evidence, evaluates submissions of both parties, and pronounces judgment after judicial scrutiny of facts and law. Contested divorce proceedings may involve detailed evidentiary stages and cross-examination. </p>
      </div> </section> 
   <section class="px-5 py-[70px]"> 
      <div class="max-w-[1100px] mx-auto">
         <h2 class="text-[clamp(26px,3vw,34px)] font-extrabold mb-5 text-slate-800 relative after:content-[&#39;&#39;] after:block after:w-[70px] after:h-1 after:bg-pink-600 after:mt-2 after:rounded"> Grounds for Divorce </h2>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2] mb-3"> Divorce may be sought on statutory grounds prescribed under applicable personal laws. The petitioner must prove the existence of such grounds before the court. </p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2] mb-3"> Common legally recognized grounds include: </p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2] mb-3"> • Cruelty – Physical or mental conduct causing harm or distress.<br/> • Desertion – Continuous abandonment without reasonable cause for statutory period.<br/> • Adultery – Voluntary sexual relationship outside marriage.<br/> • Conversion – Change of religion affecting matrimonial relationship.<br/> • Mental Disorder – Severe mental illness affecting marital obligations.<br/> • Other statutory grounds depending upon personal law. </p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2]"> Each ground requires independent proof and must satisfy the legal standards established through judicial precedents. </p>
      </div> </section> 
   <section class="bg-purple-50 border-y border-purple-100 px-5 py-[70px]"> 
      <div class="max-w-[1100px] mx-auto bg-white p-10 rounded-[18px] shadow-xl">
         <h2 class="text-[clamp(26px,3vw,34px)] font-extrabold mb-5 text-slate-800 relative after:content-[&#39;&#39;] after:block after:w-[70px] after:h-1 after:bg-pink-600 after:mt-2 after:rounded"> Divorce Procedure </h2>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2] mb-3"> Divorce proceedings generally follow a structured judicial process: </p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2] mb-3"> 1. Drafting and filing of a detailed divorce petition.<br/> 2. Issuance of notice and service upon the opposite party.<br/> 3. Filing of written statement and reply (in contested cases).<br/> 4. Framing of issues by the court.<br/> 5. Recording of evidence and cross-examination of witnesses.<br/> 6. Final arguments and submission of legal propositions.<br/> 7. Pronouncement of judgment and grant of divorce decree. </p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2]"> In mutual consent matters, the procedure involves filing of joint petition, recording of statements of parties, and satisfaction of the court before granting final decree. </p>
      </div> </section> 
   <section class="px-5 py-[70px]"> 
      <div class="max-w-[1100px] mx-auto">
         <h2 class="text-[clamp(26px,3vw,34px)] font-extrabold mb-5 text-slate-800 relative after:content-[&#39;&#39;] after:block after:w-[70px] after:h-1 after:bg-pink-600 after:mt-2 after:rounded"> Timeline of Divorce Proceedings </h2>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2] mb-3"> The duration of divorce proceedings depends upon the nature of the case, cooperation between parties, and complexity of factual disputes. </p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2] mb-3"> Mutual consent divorces generally conclude within a shorter judicial timeframe, subject to statutory procedural requirements. Contested divorces may take longer due to evidence recording, cross-examination, and judicial scrutiny. </p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2]"> Timely legal preparation and proper documentation significantly influence procedural efficiency. </p>
      </div> </section> 
   <section class="bg-purple-50 border-y border-purple-100 px-5 py-[70px]"> 
      <div class="max-w-[1100px] mx-auto bg-white p-10 rounded-[18px] shadow-xl">
         <h2 class="text-[clamp(26px,3vw,34px)] font-extrabold mb-5 text-slate-800 relative after:content-[&#39;&#39;] after:block after:w-[70px] after:h-1 after:bg-pink-600 after:mt-2 after:rounded"> Settlement &amp; Final Decree </h2>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2] mb-3"> Upon completion of proceedings, the court grants a decree of divorce, legally dissolving the marriage. </p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2] mb-3"> In mutual consent cases, settlement terms agreed between parties are recorded and form part of the judicial decree. In contested matters, the court independently evaluates the evidence and legal submissions before pronouncing judgment. </p>
         <p class="text-slate-600 leading-[2]"> The decree of divorce restores both parties to their independent legal status. </p>
      </div> </section> 
